            <p class="text-white mb-4">This article examines how the Panchos, a group of land occupiers in Mexico City, have created eight autonomous communities that challenge the dominant urban order. Drawing on Ivan Illich's critique of institutionality and recent theories of destituent power, the article shows how the Panchos practice a communal and dignified form of life that refuses and abandons the state and its institutions. The article argues that the Panchos' destituent praxis is an example of emancipatory politics that builds alternative ways of living in the present.</p>
