              <h4 class="text-white font-bold mb-2">Building Urban Autonomy: The Construction of a Communal Form of Life in Mexico City&apos;s Peripheries</h4>
              <p class="text-white mb-4">This article examines how the Comunidad Habitacional Acapatzingo, an autonomous community of around 3,000 people in the peripheries of Mexico City, has transformed from a squatted land filled with rubble into a space of urban autonomy and communal life. Drawing on ethnographic fieldwork and the concept of destituent power, the author analyzes how the community has developed its own forms of organization, communication, education, health care, and agriculture that challenge the dominant modes of urban governance and capitalism. The article argues that autonomy is not a fixed state or goal, but a dynamic process of creating and sustaining other worlds and communal forms of life in the face of multiple threats and challenges.</p>
